@NODE SCRIPT "303scripts"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Short guide about the scripts that can be loaded in the 303emu, and how
you can make them yourself -> Updated 10-09-97 by Jeroen Schellekens.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

Does the script-option suck?
----------------------------
Yes. (But at the moment, it's the only way to make acid-baselines!)

What's tha meaning of it?
-------------------------
With 303scripts you can make a list of sounds (samples) where each sound
can have it's own settings, and there's no limit of how many sounds u want
to render. Each sound that will be rendered can have all available
parameters used in the 303emulator, but it isn't nescessery to program each
parameter its value for a sound, so you can set the first sound all its
parameters to certain values, and the second sound can be modified by only
one parameter or two, while unchanged parameters, set with the first sound,
will be used. The scripts can be made and edited with a text-editor.


The commands.
---------------
The following commands are available now (in future more 2 come!):
(All commands must be lowercase!!!!!!!!)

Sound-parameters (sound params always have a value stuck to it!):

w : waveform. Values: 0=sawtooth, 1=square.
t : tuning. Values between 20 and 719 are possible.
c : cutoff frequency. value between 1 and 256 are possible.
r : resonance. Values between 0.00 and 1.00 are possible (floats).
e : envelope. Values between 0.00 and 1.00 (floats).
d : decay. Values between 1 and 200.
a : accent. Values between 1.00 and 2.00 are possible (floats).
p : volume level. Values between 0.00 and 4.00 (floats).
o : distortion. Values between 1.00 and 4.00 (floats).
g : glide up or down. Values: 0=down, 1=up.
l : glide level. Values between 0 and 1.2 (floats).
s : glide start-point. Values between 1 and 200.
z : glide end-point. Values between 1 and 200.
h : highpass-level. Values between 0 and 127.
v : overdrive-level. Values between 1 and 10.
x : Hold Fc. Values between 1 and 256.
f : Resofall. Values between 1 and 100.

Other commands:

the '-' sign : means that it is an empty sample. So there will be saved a
              sample that is empty! This is very useful, if you want to make
              a loop of your script-rendered samples (see below). - commands
              have the effect that there is no sample at that point in the
              loop, so at that point it will be quiet or the last sample
              will be played until its end. It's unmissable to make loops.

end : This means that the script has ended. This command must be set
      always, or the stuff will crash (I think. Try it out yourself!)

scriptbas 'filename' : sets the basename of the sample that will be
                       rendered (optional, a defaultname will be used, if
                       not set. This defaultname is set in the "def.pref"
                       file you can find in "303emu2:system/", and you can
                       edit that def.pref file in a normal ASCII-editor.)

makeloop bpm___ hz_____ 'filename' : make a loop of the 'til now rendered
                                     samples, and after the word bpm a
                                     value must be stuck, between 25 and
                                     255. Bpm stands for beats per minute
                                     and determines the tempo. Second, the
                                     hz must be en tered followed with the
                                     frequency in Hertz. Then, a filename
                                     must be given. So for example
                                     something like this --+
                                                           |
makeloop bpm140 hz22000 'work:loop1'              <--------+

                                     Also, this command is optional, not
                                     necessery.

The structure of a script.
--------------------------
Next, you see an example script:


'303-example-script
'© 1996 Jeroen Schellekens

scriptbas 'work:303emu2/sample.'

t230  c16  r0.996  e0.06  d4  a1  p1.4   o1  g0  l0    s1  z1  w0
t220  c15
t192  c16
t192  c15
t180  c16                 d10                    l0.15 s9  z14
-
t220  c19                 d4                     l0            w1
t180               e0.1

makeloop bpm125 hz17000 'work:303testloopa'

end



The head of the script begins with a ' sign, followed some text. This '
sign means that it is a remark, so you can write information after it to
remember what it or something else, while it hasn't got any effect or
function for the program. It's just handy for you.

Also, spaces and empty lines have no function or effect, they just make
it more arranged for you.

Then we see a word scriptbas followed by two ' signs with a path and name
between them. "scriptbas" is the short for script-base-sample-name or
something like that, and it's function is the basename for the sample that
will be saved. After this basename, the number of the sample will be
added, such as "sample.001".

Again, remember that all the commands must be lowercase, not uppercase,
or it will not work!

Then we see (after an empty line) a set of characters, and stuck to them
you see values. The command is the parameter, and the value is ... the
value that belongs to that parameter. So in the current line the first
parameter is t (for tuning) and its value is 230.
You see, the first line with parameters contains many parameters or
commands, but the second one contains only a tuning (t220) and different
cutoff frequency (c15). This means that the first sample uses the values of
the first line, and the second one uses the the two commands its values,
and the other parameters will not change, so will the same in the second
sample.
Also the following order of the commands isn't important.

The - means that there will be an empty place or sample.

makeloop makes a loop of all samples into one new sample. Now this is where
the - sign comes in. Its function is that on the 6th place, no sound will 
be heard and that the 5th sample will play to its end. The tempo is
controlled by bpm, in this case 125 beats per minute. The hz-command 
determines the playbackrate, and the higher the value after it, the higher
the quality will be. Last, the name of the sample must be given, between to
' signs.

Then we see end, and this command must be in every script. If not, the
program will not know that it is ready, and will loop until you reset your
computer.


For those who work with the script-function, and hate to just guess
what pitch to enter, here is a list (A 2 is 440 Hz/ 254period):

A  1: 508      A  2: 254      A  3: 127      A  4: 63
A# 1: 479      A# 2: 239      A# 3: 119      A# 4: 59
B  1: 452      B  2: 226      B  3: 113      B  4: 56
C  1: 427      C  2: 213      C  3: 106      C  4: 53
C# 1: 403      C# 2: 201      C# 3: 100      C# 4: 50
D  1: 380      D  2: 190      D  3: 95       D  4: 47
D# 1: 359      D# 2: 179      D# 3: 89       D# 4: 44
E  1: 339      E  2: 169      E  3: 84       E  4: 42
F  1: 320      F  2: 160      F  3: 80       F  4: 40
F# 1: 302      F# 2: 151      F# 3: 75       F# 4: 37
G  1: 285      G  2: 142      G  3: 71       G  4: 35
G# 1: 269      G# 2: 134      G# 3: 67       G# 4: 33

So if you want to make a sample in the script, with a pitch of the C-2,
enter something like this:

t213  c145  r0.98   e0.6  d12  a1  p1.2   o1  g0  l0     s1  z1  w0 v2

(Where 't213' means 'tuning 213', and 'c145' stands for 'cutoff 145'.)


Hope I've given enough explanation 'bout the script-language.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
@ENDNODE

@NODE FAQ "Frequently Asked Questions"

Frequently Asked Questions about the 303emulator V2.2c


The startup procedure/installation

Q: I have a VGA-monitor connected to my Amiga. Can I use the 303emulator
   with it?
A: Only, if your VGA-monitor supports the PAL-format: 15.625 kHz. Also, be
   sure your monitor-prefs are set to PAL, and your screen-mode is Hires,
   Hires Laced. Most of the PC VGA-monitor can't handle frequencies like
   PAL. Their lowest freq. mode is often 30 kHz. But there are VGA-monitors
   that CAN handle 15.625 kHz. Also, Amiga-made-Multiscan & 1084 monitors can
   always handle PAL-mode. Read the manual of your Monitor to check it.

Q: I have my workbench set in DBPAL/Productivity/DBLNTSC mode. Can I use
   the 303emulator now?
A: No. You have to set your monitorpreferences to a PAL mode. And your
   screenmode must be Hires, Hires Laced. This is because the 303emulator
   wants to startup in the PAL-screen mode, at 15.625 kHz.

Q: The 303emulator won't startup. How come?
A: Maybe you haven't set your monitor to PAL, and your Workbench runs under
   Productivity, DBPAL, DBNTSC or something like that. You have to set it
   to PAL, and choose a screenmode like Hires, or Hires Laced.
   What also could be the problem, is that the installing procedure went
   wrong bcoz your Harddisk was full. Or maybe you changed, deleted or moved
   a directory or file, that the 303 emulator needs. Try to reinstall the
   303emulator, and delete before doing that, the old 303emulator
   directory. What also could be is that an assign, that the 303emu need to
   find its files, was changed or removed. Be sure that the following
   assign is made: Assign 303emu2: work:directory. 'work:directory' depends
   on where yu placed yur 303emulator, but be sure that the 303emulator-
   files are in this path. Normally, the assign is made in your
   user-startup in your S-directory by the 303emu-installation-script.
   Never touch or change the system-files, found in 303emu2:system/ !!!!!

Q: Can I run 303emulator on a NTSC-system?
A: Yes it can. The full screen will not fit on an NTSC-Amiga, but you can
   move the screen, by moving the mouse up and down.

Q: Once the 303emu worked on my Amiga. Now it won't startup anymore. Why?
A: Maybe you changed some files or directories the 303emu needs. Reinstall
   it with the 303-install-script.


The program itself, Q & A about the 303emu...

Q: What's the meaning of 303emu, or what can I use it for?
A: 303emu is a sound rendering program, wich emulates the sound of the
   Roland TB-303. It's function is to generate acid-baselines, save them as
   a sample, and then use it in a music program like
   Protracker/Octamed/Musiclineeditor/Digibooster.

Q: When the 303emu has started, and I see a screen with lots of knobs and
   buttons, what's next?
A: You now see the main screen of the 303emu. For some fun, press the
   SPACE-BAR. You now hear a sound. Play a bit with the rotary knobs
   'Cutoff, 'Tune' or 'Resonance' of the first set of parameters, and
   again, press SPACE-BAR. You'll notice the sound will be a bit different.
   If you like it, you can calculate a better sounding version of it, by
   pressing on the button 'Render' (bottom left). Once it's ready (you will
   hear a beep), you can play the result, by pressing 'Play'. Read the
   'Guide trough the program' for more details.

Q: Where are all those rotary knobs for?
A: To change the timbre of the sound, wich will be calculated. The sound
   is a single sound, one tone, when set in 'Single Mode'.

Q: I changed some parameters, adjusted some knobs. Now what?
A: To get a result, you'll have to render it. Press 'Render'. Then, when
   it's ready, press 'Play'. You will now hear a sound. You can also press
   SPACE-BAR, anytime in the main-screen, to get a preview of the sound.
   If you want to save the sample, you press 'Save Sample'.

Q: What's the switch 'Single'/'Sequence' for?
A: If you set the switch to 'Single Mode', the program will calculate one
   single tone/sound, if you press the 'Render' button. It uses all the
   parameters for it. If the swith is set to 'Sequence Mode', and you press
   'Render Sequence', it will ask you to specify a name, with a
    filerequester. Then, it calculates a range of samples, wich uses
   Parameterbox A as the first sample, Parambox B as the last sample. The
   number of samples are set with the knob, aside 'Render Sequence'. All
   the samples that will be rendered, also will be saved. So Parambox A and
   B function as a sort of key frames.

Q: What are the buttons 'test' and 'save' for (bottom right)?
A: These are to play and save the realtime preview of the 303-sound. It's a
   single sound, wich uses the parameters in the parameter-boxes A & B.

Q: When I set the waveform to 'Square', and I press Space-bar, or press the
   'Test'-button, the sound is the same as the 'Sawtooth'. Why?
A: This is an ommission I will correct it in a new version.

Q: What is the 'Plug-In' button for?
A: It's an option to get new extra functions and parameters in the 303emu.
   For now, I've not written one plug-in yet. It's the filter-selector. In
   future there will come other plug ins, liek an envelope-editor. Read the
   Future-list.

Q: How do I make a complete riff or baseline?
A: You have to make a script. You make one, with a text-editor like CED.
   Then, you import it in the 303emu, via the 'Script'-button in the middle
   of the screen. How you have to make a script, is explained in
   @{" How to make 303scripts     " link SCRIPT}. With the 303emu, I've
   included some example-scripts. You can find them in 303emu2:scripts,
   and edit them in a text-editor. I know, it sucks, but I am working on a
   script-editor.

Q: Why are there 2 sets of knobs with 'Tune', 'Cutoff', 'Resonance' etc.?
A: This is because, when turned into 'Sequence Mode', you can use them
   as a sort of key frames. Parambox A supposes the first sample, B the
   last sample. In Single Mode, you can check the result of a parameterbox
   by rendering (Render Single) it or previewing it (Space-bar). It will
   render or preview the Parambox, that's selected. There's a cursor
   flashing around the (A) for Parambox A, or (B) for box B. To select A or
   B, just press on the (A) or (B). Now the cursor will flash on it.

Q: What is the flashing box around the (A) or (B) for?
A: Read the answer above.

Q: How do I get the same settings in Parameterbox B as A?
A: Press with the left mousebutton on A. Hold it and drag it to the (B).
   This copies A to B. To copy Parambox B to A, drag the (B) to (A).
   When you hold instead of the left one, the right mousebutton, you can
   swap the sets. Handy isn't it?

Q: I changed a lot of settingss, and now I can't get a nice sound of it
   anymore. How do I reset it?
A: Press the 'NEW' button (middle of screen), or load a Parameter.

Q: Is there a sequencer in the 303emu?
A: No, only a script-option.

Q: Why do I sometimes have to save a sample, and sometimes not?
A: You only have to save the sample by hand, if you are in 'Single mode'.
   Else, if you are in 'Sequence Mode', 303emu asks you automaticly where
   to save the samples. In script-mode, the script itself already saves the
   samples.

Q: What format does the 303emu save its samples?
A: 8 bit iff-8svx, in script-mode also 8 bit Raw.

Q: How do I abort the rendering progress, or a script that is executing?
A: Hold down both mousebuttons for a while, until you hear a beep. Then it
   returns to the mainscreen agin.

Misc. Questions:

Q: Is the 303emu v2.2c Midi-controllable?
A: No, the 303emu does NOT support any MIDI-stuff.

Q: I've heard of a 303sequencer for Amiga. What is it?
A: It's an unofficial program to program 303-riffs, and play it i realtime.
   It supports MIDI-sync, alothough it's full of bugs.

Q: Is 303emu written in Amos?
A: Yes! Funny in't it? Not? .........shut up.....

Q: Will there be a ASM- or C-version in future?
A: If I find people who can do it for me...where are you!?

Q: Does 303emu support 16 bit samples?
A: No, not yet. Will come in (near) future.

Q: Will 303emu be developed further?
A: Yes, there will be first: a script/riff-editor, then a 16 bit saver,
   then an envelope-editor, and then I am dead maybe.

Q: Does Amos suck?
A: After 3 years of using it: yes.

Q: When does a new version of 303emu come out?
A: Soon, every month I will spread a new version.

Q: Is 303emu coded badly?
A: The first parts of the program are indeed, as I started learning to
   program when I started writing 303emu. Are you rest assured now?

Q: How does the real TB-303 sequencer work?
A: It's quite magic how it exactly works, but it partly goes like this:

   First you program a melody in step-time mode. Then you say how long a
   note must be: 8th, 16th or a rest note. Then you add accent and slide to
   the notes. Then you play it, while tweaking the rotary knobs.
   The slide is prenote they told me. The result will always be the exact
   pitch and time of the note it has slided to. The accent is a very much
   talked issue too: it probably adjusts ONLY the resonance and VCA.
   Although you hear that the envelope is changed too. What I think myself
   is that the cutoff is set a bit higher at the beginning, but then the
   filter closes faster than normal. But I still am not sure! It's a
   fucking strange machine man!

@ENDNODE

@node env

303emu's parameter-appendix.
----------------------------
In this appendix, all parameters found in the 303emu are described how they
work, what their boundaries are, wich settings to get wich results, and how
to control them well to get what you want.



The 6 basic TB-303 parameters.
------------------------------
These are the equivalents to the 6 rotary knobs on the real TB-303 above.


Tuning - Value range (boundaries)  : 1 - 720.
         Often used range of values: between 100 and 300.

         This determines the pitch of the sound you want to make. Note that
         the value you assign, is the PERIOD of the sound. This means, that
         a higher value means that the period is larger. The BIGGER the
         period size, the LOWER the sound will be.
         If you push on the \/ button, you will get a preset list of notes
         to convert to a    ŻŻ
         period. This is very handy if you want an exact value, without
         experimenting what value you have to enter to get a good result.

         To get a 'normal' 303 basstone, I often use the value of D#2: 179.
         this is a good starting pitch to begin with...

         In case of, here's a list:

         A  1: 508      A  2: 254      A  3: 127      A  4: 63
         A# 1: 479      A# 2: 239      A# 3: 119      A# 4: 59
         B  1: 452      B  2: 226      B  3: 113      B  4: 56
         C  1: 427      C  2: 213      C  3: 106      C  4: 53
         C# 1: 403      C# 2: 201      C# 3: 100      C# 4: 50
         D  1: 380      D  2: 190      D  3: 95      D  4: 47
         D# 1: 359      D# 2: 179      D# 3: 89      D# 4: 44
         E  1: 339      E  2: 169      E  3: 84      E  4: 42
         F  1: 320      F  2: 160      F  3: 80      F  4: 40
         F# 1: 302      F# 2: 151      F# 3: 75      F# 4: 37
         G  1: 285      G  2: 142      G  3: 71      G  4: 35
         G# 1: 269      G# 2: 134      G# 3: 67      G# 4: 33



Cutoff - Value range (boundaries)  : 1 - 256.
         Often used range of values: between 10 and 120.

         This parameter has great effect on the timbre of the 303 sound.
         It determines the cut off frequency of the filter, to start
         filtering. Every frequency in the sound, that's higher than this
         value, will be filtered out, and will not be heard anymore.

         The combination of the cut off parameter with a high amount of
         resonance gives the right snoring acid-sound.

         The higher the value, the more brightness & detail of the sound is
         left. When you set a low value, like 10 or 20, it will sound dull
         and dark. When you set values higher than 120, the sound will be
         not a lot different anymore. When you set values lower than 6, the
         sound will be very soft and a value of 1 will filter all
         frequencies and what's left is hardly any sound.

         To get aggressive bass pumping sounds, try values of 10-26.
         To get the more squeeky acid-loop sounds, use values like 50-100.

         IMPORTANT: To get the well known acid-sound, you also have to set
         the resonance to a high value!

Resonance - Value range (boundaries)  : 0.000 - 1.000.
            Often used range of values: between 0.9 and 1 (much resonance);
                                        between 0.0 and 0.1 (no resonance).

            Very important parameter in combination with cutoff.
            Use high values like 0.96 - 0.99 to get squeeky 303 bleeps.

            As my 303emu has a more Korg MS-10/20 filter than the original
            TB-303, you might get strange results, when you set the
            resonance at values of 0.5.
            Because this resonance parameter isn't linear, it also doesn't
            mean that when you set resonance half open (0.5), you have half
            resonance.

            If you want no resonance in your sound try values like 0 - 0.3.
            The higher your value, starting from 0, the less 'bass' your
            sound will have. But, when you reach the point of 0.9, the
            sound exponentially starts to get squeeking!


Envelope - Value range (boundaries)  : 0.000 - 1.000.
           Often used range of values: 0.02 (smooth slow envelope);
                                       0.4  (quick aggressive envelope).

           The higher the value of this parameter, the faster the sound
           will change from bright to dull. In technical terms, it closes 
           the filter (throws cut off frequency down). The impact of it
           depends on the value. To get short fast notes, use values like
           0.2 - 0.5, for slowly changing notes, use 0.01 - 0.1.

Decay - Value range (boundaries)  : 1 - 200 (360 - 72000 bytes).
        Often used range of values: 6 - 16.

        In fact, this parameter controls, how long your sound will be,
        in bytes.
        When you set a value of 1, your sound will be 360 bytes long.
        When you set a value of 200, it will be 72000 bytes long.

        Length in bytes=Decay value*(360/Tuning).

        BUT, when, cause of the other settings you've made (like cut off,
        envelope), the calculated sound doesn't have any information (read
        sound) anymore at a certain point, it will stop rendering and the
        size of the calculated sound will be 'till that point.

        So, if yu've set the deacy to 100, it theoreticly will result a
        sound of 36000 bytes, but, when you set a low cut off like 8, and
        a high envlope, say 0.5, There will be no sound left after about 
        2000 bytes. Then it's unneseccery to hold and save a sample of 
        36000 bytes, if there's only a real sound of 2000 bytes, get it?

Accent - Value range (boundaries)  : 1.00 -2.00
         Often used range of values: 1 (No accent;
                                     2 (Full accent).

         I read in the Cu Amiga mag. that this parameter has hardly any
         influence. Damned right it has! You just have to use extreme 
         values, just like the resonance parameter.
         
         The accent does a couple of things to the 303 sound.
         (As i read a mailing list about how the real 303 works, I learned 
         some new things about eg. the Accent works.)
         The accent in MY 303emu does the following:
         
         The higher the Accent's value, the more pump will put in the
         sound. More accent, more energy. The result is an increase of 
         volume, resonance and envelope modulation. As it's a very 
         mysterious parameter, on the real TB-303, I don't know exactly how
         the real one works. They say it's only the volume and resonance 
         that's screwed up, depending on the amount of resonance, but when 
         I saw the service docs of the 303, I noticed also a line from the
         accent to the envelope. You also hear it in da real 1: when notes
         have accent, they sound harder, more squeeky, a tickle more
         bright (cutoff freq. higher?), but then faster duller (cut off
         lower). Who knows how it really works, has to contact me and 
         explain it 2 me!


The Glide parameters.
---------------------
As I didn't had a good solution to implement the glide function when I
started to write this program, I came up with sort of a pitch bender idea.
The original TB-303 glide lets one note stretch its frequency/pitch to the
next note, that will be played. When, by adjusting the frequency of the
first note, reaches the pitch of the upcoming one, this next one will be
played. My alternative, is that you create a note with a certain pitch, and
changes its pitch in time, to another pitch, and when it reaches this new
(prepogrammed) pitch, it offers the opportunity to play this one a while.
I explain it a bit complicated here, but in fact it's very simple.

303emu gives you 4 parameters to get the result you want:

Start-Sets the start point (in periods) to bend the pitch
Stop-Sets the point (in periods) to stop bending the pitch
Up/down- sets to glide up or down, or to go to a higher or lower tone.
Level- sets the amount of gliding.

I have to admit that this way of creating a slide/glide is not the easiest
one, and I know now there are better ways, so I'll do something about it in
next versions.

As I know it's a bit shit to get good results, I implemented a little help,
by giving you the resulted period.

Level - Value range (boundaries)  : 0.000 - 1.200
        Often used range of values: 0 (NO GLIDE AT ALL);

                                    0.08 (normal glide).
@ENDNODE

